feed: {'title': 'Google lines up with Apple and Microsoft to nix passwords in favor of nearby-device authentication', 'url': 'https://www.fastcompany.com/90749268/google-lines-up-with-apple-and-microsoft-to-nix-passwords-in-favor-of-nearby-device-authentication', 'time_published': '20220505T130013', 'authors': [], 'summary': 'No, not by falling back to some easily-memorized password, but by using your smartphone to log you into another nearby device of yours, such as your laptop. Google has announced that it would support a passwordless sign-on system in the Android and Chrome operating systems. In addition, Apple and Microsoft said they will do the same in their operating systems and browsers. That will allow you to mix and match platforms-say, using an Android phone to whisk you into an account in Safari on a Mac, or an iPhone to log in on Edge on a Windows PC. It will work a bit like a USB security key does now for a laptop or desktop, except that where those compact fobs from Yubico and others still expect you to type in your password first on that device, here unlocking your phone near the other computer will suffice. These joint announcements on World Password Day  ( one of the worst celebrations of bureaucratic annoyance, after Tax Day ) , builds on earlier moves to eliminate the password as the primary defense for an account.', 'banner_image': 'https://images.fastcompany.net/image/upload/w_1280,f_auto,q_auto,fl_lossy/wp-cms/uploads/2022/05/p-1-google-lines-up-with-apple-and-microsoft-to-nix-passwords-in-favor-of-nearby-device-authentication.jpg', 'source': 'Fast Company', 'category_within_source': 'n/a', 'source_domain': 'www.fastcompany.com', 'topics': [{'topic': 'Technology', 'relevance_score': '1.0'}], 'overall_sentiment_score': 0.16558, 'overall_sentiment_label': 'Somewhat-Bullish', 'ticker_sentiment': [{'ticker': 'MSFT', 'relevance_score': '0.060725', 'ticker_sentiment_score': '0.375672', 'ticker_sentiment_label': 'Bullish'}, {'ticker': 'GOOG', 'relevance_score': '0.180775', 'ticker_sentiment_score': '0.16558', 'ticker_sentiment_label': 'Somewhat-Bullish'}]}

feed: {'title': 'Why this climate scientist now works for a car company', 'url': 'https://www.fastcompany.com/90748267/why-this-climate-scientist-now-works-for-a-car-company', 'time_published': '20220506T110011', 'authors': [], 'summary': '"I was feeling, increasingly, this imperative to get involved in the emissions reduction side," says Reeder, who now serves as the director of both sustainability and government affairs for Audi of America. He had worked to try to pass a cap-and-trade law in the state of Washington, but the bill failed, leading him to feel frustrated with the political process-and to think more about the potential of working in industry. By 2016, as transportation surpassed electricity as the biggest source of emissions in the U.S., "transportation was sort of in the crosshairs for everybody in the climate community," he says. Part of making transportation more climate-friendly will come from walkable neighborhoods and better public transit. But Reeder knew that car companies like Audi would also have to fundamentally change, pivoting from a long history of making internal combustion engines, or ICEs.  ( Audi is among the oldest automakers, having spun out of a company first founded in 1899. )  In 2018, he sat down with the president of Audi of America at the time, Scott Chico, to interview for the company\'s sustainability director job. "I looked him in the eye and we interviewed each other, essentially," he says. "I just said, how serious are you about making this pivot to electric vehicles? And how serious are you about the underlying context that this is a climate imperative-like, you\'re not just doing this because Tesla\'s your competitor, and this is sort of a cool business opportunity. . . . Is there a systemic commitment to addressing climate change?"', 'banner_image': 'https://images.fastcompany.net/image/upload/w_1280,f_auto,q_auto,fl_lossy/wp-cms/uploads/2022/05/p-1-90748267-why-this-climate-scientist-now-works-for-a-car-company.jpg', 'source': 'Fast Company', 'category_within_source': 'n/a', 'source_domain': 'www.fastcompany.com', 'topics': [{'topic': 'Mergers & Acquisitions', 'relevance_score': '0.158519'}, {'topic': 'Technology', 'relevance_score': '0.5'}, {'topic': 'Manufacturing', 'relevance_score': '0.5'}], 'overall_sentiment_score': 0.047249, 'overall_sentiment_label': 'Neutral', 'ticker_sentiment': [{'ticker': 'AA', 'relevance_score': '0.044027', 'ticker_sentiment_score': '0.23799', 'ticker_sentiment_label': 'Somewhat-Bullish'}, {'ticker': 'MSFT', 'relevance_score': '0.044027', 'ticker_sentiment_score': '-0.082202', 'ticker_sentiment_label': 'Neutral'}, {'ticker': 'GM', 'relevance_score': '0.044027', 'ticker_sentiment_score': '0.04477', 'ticker_sentiment_label': 'Neutral'}]}

feed: {'title': 'Welcome to the era of the hyper-surveilled office', 'url': 'https://www.economist.com/business/2022/05/09/welcome-to-the-era-of-the-hyper-surveilled-office', 'time_published': '20220509T000000', 'authors': [], 'summary': "BOSSES HAVE always kept tabs on their workers.
